<refentry id="CapabilitiesEngine">
<?dbhtml filename="config_ref_CapabilitiesEngine.html">
<refentryinfo>
  <keywordset>
    <keyword>
      mod_cap
    </keyword>
  </keywordset>
</refentryinfo>
<refmeta>
<refentrytitle>
<indexterm><primary>CapabilitiesEngine</primary></indexterm>
CapabilitiesEngine
</refentrytitle>
</refmeta>
<refnamediv>
<refname>CapabilitiesEngine</refname>
<refpurpose>Enable/disable mod_cap</refpurpose>
</refnamediv>

<refsynopsisdiv>
<cmdsynopsis>
<command>CapabilitiesEngine</command>
<arg choice="opt">
  <option>on</option>
  <option>off</option>
</arg>
</cmdsynopsis>

<variablelist><title></title>
<varlistentry><term><synopsis>Default</synopsis></term>
<listitem> <para>
CapabilitiesEngine On, if running on a Linux hosts that supports capabilities
</para> </listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry><term><synopsis>Context</synopsis></term>
<listitem> <para>
server config, &lt;VirtualHost&gt;, &lt;Global&gt;
</para> </listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry><term><synopsis>Module</synopsis></term>
<listitem> <para>
mod_cap
</para> </listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry><term><synopsis>Compatibility</synopsis></term>
<listitem> <para>
1.2.8rc1 and later
</para> </listitem>
</varlistentry>
</variablelist>
</refsynopsisdiv>

<refsect1>
  <title>Description</title>
  <para>The CapabilitiesEngine directive enables or disables the module's
  runtime capabilities engine. If set to off, this module does no runtime
  capabilities processing at all. Use this directive to disable the
  module.</para>
</refsect1>
</refentry>
